Framing the problem

The goal is to use the California Housing Prices dataset to build a model that forecasts housing prices. Using the independent variablesincome, population, and householdswe are attempting to predict the values of the dependent variable, or house value, and we plan to do so by using linear regression.


Importing packages

In[1]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn import linear_model
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error

Source: Downloaded from Kaggle California Housing Prices

Data Preprocessing

Filter out records with median_house_value = 500001 since it seems to be a cap for the median_house_value.

In[9]:
housing_preprocessed = housing[housing.median_house_value != 500001]
In[10]:
print(f"After filtering, there are {len(housing_preprocessed)} records, versus {len(housing)} before filtering")

After filtering, there are 19675 records, versus 20640 before filtering

Train and Test Split

Split the data into training/testing sets. Use the first 80% of the data for training.

In[11]:
train_size = int(len(housing_preprocessed) * 0.8)
train = housing_preprocessed[:train_size]
test = housing_preprocessed[train_size:]

Linear Regressions

Creating three linear regression models for each independent variable:

  1. median house value vs. median income
  2. median house value vs. population
  3. median house value vs. number of households
In[15]:
model_income = linear_model.LinearRegression()
model_population = linear_model.LinearRegression()
model_households = linear_model.LinearRegression()

Train the Model

In[17]:
model_income.fit(X=train[["median_income"]], y=train[["median_house_value"]])
model_population.fit(X=train[["population"]], y=train[["median_house_value"]])
model_households.fit(X=train[["households"]], y=train[["median_house_value"]])

Model Evaluation

In[61]:
income_mse_train = mean_squared_error(train[["median_house_value"]], model_income.predict(train[["median_income"]]))
income_mae_train = mean_absolute_error(train[["median_house_value"]], model_income.predict(train[["median_income"]]))

pop_mse_train = mean_squared_error(train[["median_house_value"]], model_population.predict(train[["population"]]))
pop_mae_train = mean_absolute_error(train[["median_house_value"]], model_population.predict(train[["population"]]))
 
households_mse_train = mean_squared_error(train[["median_house_value"]], model_households.predict(train[["households"]]))
households_mae_train = mean_absolute_error(train[["median_house_value"]], model_households.predict(train[["households"]]))
 
income_mse_test = mean_squared_error(test[["median_house_value"]], model_income.predict(test[["median_income"]]))
income_mae_test = mean_absolute_error(test[["median_house_value"]], model_income.predict(test[["median_income"]]))

pop_mse_test = mean_squared_error(test[["median_house_value"]], model_population.predict(test[["population"]]))
pop_mae_test = mean_absolute_error(test[["median_house_value"]], model_population.predict(test[["population"]]))

households_mse_test = mean_squared_error(test[["median_house_value"]], model_households.predict(test[["households"]])) 
households_mae_test = mean_absolute_error(test[["median_house_value"]], model_households.predict(test[["households"]]))
 
 
evaluations = pd.DataFrame({
    'Model': ['Median Income', 'Population', 'Households'],
    'Intercept': [model_income.intercept_[0], model_population.intercept_[0], model_households.intercept_[0]],
    'Slope': [model_income.coef_[0][0], model_population.coef_[0][0], model_households.coef_[0][0]],
    'Mean Squared Error TRAIN': [income_mse_train , pop_mse_train, households_mse_train],
    'Mean Absolute Error TRAIN': [income_mae_train, pop_mae_train, households_mae_train],
    'Mean Squared Error TEST': [income_mse_test, pop_mse_test, households_mse_test],
    'Mean Absolute Error TEST': [income_mae_test, pop_mae_test, households_mae_test]
})
 
evaluations['Intercept'] = evaluations['Intercept'].map('{:.2f}'.format)
evaluations['Slope'] = evaluations['Slope'].map('{:.2f}'.format)
evaluations['Mean Squared Error TRAIN'] = evaluations['Mean Squared Error TRAIN'].map('{:.2f}'.format)
evaluations['Mean Squared Error TEST'] = evaluations['Mean Squared Error TEST'].map('{:.2f}'.format)
evaluations['Mean Absolute Error TRAIN'] = evaluations['Mean Absolute Error TRAIN'].map('{:.2f}'.format)
evaluations['Mean Absolute Error TEST'] = evaluations['Mean Absolute Error TEST'].map('{:.2f}'.format)
 
 
display(evaluations.T)

Plotting the regression line

  1. Plot the regression line against the training data for median_income model
In[65]:
sns.scatterplot(x="median_income", y="median_house_value", data=train, color="blue")
plt.plot(train[["median_income"]], model_income.predict(train[["median_income"]]), color="black", linewidth=3)
textstr = (f'Intercept: {model_income.intercept_[0]:.2f}\n'
           f'Slope: {model_income.coef_[0][0]:.2f}\n'
           f'MSE: {mean_squared_error(train[["median_house_value"]], model_income.predict(train[["median_income"]])):.2f}\n'
           f'MAE: {mean_absolute_error(train[["median_house_value"]], model_income.predict(train[["median_income"]])):.2f}')
props = dict(boxstyle='square', facecolor='grey', alpha=0.3)
plt.text(0.02, 0.99, textstr, transform=plt.gca().transAxes, fontsize=12,
             verticalalignment='top', bbox=props)
plt.title("Median Income vs Median House Value")
plt.show()

SUMMARY

Following an analysis of each model's performance, the following conclusions can be drawn:

  1. We can observe that the median income model works better than the other two models since it has the lowest MSE and MAE, indicating that it is more accurate for the provided dataset.
  2. In terms of accuracy, the Households model falls in between the other two models.
  3. The population model has the largest MAE and MSE, indicating a lower degree of accuracy in the model.
  4. Compared to the other two models, the linear function that is plotted on the median income intercepts more cases.
